# 🔴 What’s ACTUALLY wrong

You are copying:

```dockerfile
COPY jfrog.crt /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/
```

But that `jfrog.crt` is **most likely only the server cert**, not:

* ❌ Root CA
* ❌ Intermediate CA

👉 So Java/Go (JFrog CLI) still says:

```
x509: certificate signed by unknown authority
```

---

# ✅ Fix (REAL SOLUTION – not workaround)

## Step 1: Extract FULL certificate chain

Run this from ANY machine that can reach Artifactory:

```bash
openssl s_client -showcerts -connect <your-artifactory-host>:443 </dev/null
```

Example:

```bash
openssl s_client -showcerts -connect artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443 </dev/null
```

---

## Step 2: You will see something like:

```
-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
(server cert)
-----END CERTIFICATE-----

-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
(intermediate CA)
-----END CERTIFICATE-----

-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
(root CA)
-----END CERTIFICATE-----
```

---

## Step 3: Combine ALL into ONE file

Create:

```bash
vi jfrog-chain.crt
```

Paste:

```
-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
(server cert)
-----END CERTIFICATE-----
-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
(intermediate CA)
-----END CERTIFICATE-----
-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
(root CA)
-----END CERTIFICATE-----
```

👉 Order matters:

```
server → intermediate → root
```

---

## Step 4: Update Dockerfile

```dockerfile
FROM registry.dev.sbiepay.sbi:8443/ubi9/gradle-8.9-jdk-21:v6

COPY jf /usr/local/bin/jf
RUN chmod +x /usr/local/bin/jf

# Use FULL CHAIN (important)
COPY jfrog-chain.crt /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/jfrog.crt

RUN update-ca-trust extract

RUN jf --version
```

---

## Step 5: Rebuild + push again

```bash
podman build -t gradle-jfrog:v9 .
podman push ...
```

